\begin_layout Subsection*
Scala Documentation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Documentation of source files isn't just for folks mucking around in your code – it can easily be summoned in the console to see what author's of any code had to say.
 For example,
 our Mood enum above is meticulously documented for maximum comprehension.
 The format is similar to a lot of other lanugaes :
 /** ...
 */,
 with some keywords to help.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The secret trick here is that you can easily summon this documentation *in the console* with 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
scala> :doc Mood
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
Represents a developer's state of mind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
 * @param intensity How strongly the mood is felt (1-10)
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
Note
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
 - Use [[Mood.Caffeinated]] for high-performance tasks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However,
 if you do prefer the nicely marked up we version,
 you can build it with
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
./scala-cli doc .
 -o ./my-docs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
from within your directory,
 and it will generate a full,
 searchable docs website in you my-docs folder (open my-docs/index.html in a browser to start navigating).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Give it a try in your command line – it may be a bit off-putting first,
 but is quite powerful the more you get used to it!
\end_layout

